==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in 1529. ''Either'' from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|abolition}}, ''or'' directly from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|abolitiō}}, from {{m|la|aboleō||destroy}}.<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=3-4}}</ref> Compare French {{m|fr|abolition}}. See {{m|en|abolish}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˌæb.əˈlɪʃ.n̩/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|EN-AU ck1 abolition.ogg|Audio (AU)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The act of [[abolish|abolishing]]; an [[annul|annulling]]; [[abrogation]] {{defdate|First attested around the early 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=6}}</ref>
#:{{ux|en|the '''abolition''' of slavery}}
#:{{ux|en|the '''abolition''' of laws}}
#:{{ux|en|the '''abolition''' of decress}}
#:{{ux|en|the '''abolition''' of taxes}}
#:{{ux|en|the '''abolition''' of debts}}
# The state of being [[abolished]]
# {{lb|en|historical|often capitalised|UK|US}} The ending of the [[slave]] trade or of [[slavery]]. {{defdate|First attested around the early 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|historical|often capitalised|Australia}} The ending of convict transportation. {{defdate|First attested around the late 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} An [[amnesty]]; a putting out of memory. {{defdate|Attested from the early 17<sup>th</sup> century to the early 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

====Usage notes====
The sense "amnesty", and in general any reference to "abolition of" a person, is now obsolete or unusual.

